stylometry: Transportation models are models in which there is a location and a destination and the products go from the location to the destination.  A transhipment problem is very similar in that it has a location and a destinations but the difference is a transshipment problem also includes a warehouse.  This adds a different dimension to the transshipment problems.  A specific example of a transhipment problem is if we have 4,000 hats in cleveland and we need to send them to  a warehouse in Akron to embroider the patches onto the hats, then ship them to miami, florida where the hats will be sold in different stores.  Nodes and arcs are the lines that connect the location to the destinations and warehouses.  I am not sure which ones these are but one of these only includes going to a specific direction whether it is coming or going.
